{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 09:21:13.630724", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and expectation\n- Target topology: RIP-routed underlay with a WireGuard VPN overlay. Internal host_1 is supposed to use the VPN to reach the external web servers web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2, which only serve HTTP on their VPN addresses (172.16.1.21/22).\n\n1) Overall network health (underlay)\n- Routing: RIP tables are present and consistent on router1, router2, gateway_router, and external_router_1. Each has expected connected and RIP-learned routes for 10.0.0.0/24, 10.0.1.0/24, 20.0.0.0/24, and inter-router /31s.\n  - Examples:\n    - router1: 20.0.0.0/24 via gateway (192.168.0.3/eth1), 10.0.1.0/24 via router2 (192.168.0.1/eth0).\n    - gateway_router: learns all three LANs via correct neighbors.\n    - external_router_1: 20.0.0.0/24 connected via br0; 10.0.0.0/24, 10.0.1.0/24 via gateway.\n- Reachability: Underlay ICMP is healthy.\n  - host_1 -> vpn_server_1 (20.0.0.2): 0% loss, ~2.7 ms avg.\n  - host_2 -> host_1 and host_2 -> vpn_server_1: 0% loss, single-digit ms.\n  - host_1 -> web_server_1_1 (20.0.0.3) and web_server_1_2 (20.0.0.4): 0% loss, low latency.\n- Conclusion: The routed underlay is normal with no evidence of loss or misrouting.\n\n2) VPN overlay health and application layer observations\n- Web servers only expose HTTP on VPN addresses:\n  - web_server_1_1: TCP LISTEN on 172.16.1.21:80.\n  - web_server_1_2: TCP LISTEN on 172.16.1.22:80.\n  - They do not listen on 20.0.0.x, matching the “VPN-only” design.\n- host_1 WireGuard interface: wg0 up with 172.16.1.11/24; peer configured to vpn_server_1 (20.0.0.2:51820). AllowedIPs on host_1 is 172.16.1.0/24.\n- vpn_server_1 WireGuard interface: wg0 up with 172.16.1.1/24; peers configured only for web_server_1_1 (172.16.1.21/32) and web_server_1_2 (172.16.1.22/32). The host_1 peer is absent (commented out) in /etc/wireguard/wg0.conf.\n- Handshake status:\n  - web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2 show recent handshakes with vpn_server_1, indicating their tunnels to the server are up.\n  - host_1 shows no handshake info and cannot send/receive via the VPN.\n- Overlay connectivity tests from host_1:\n  - ICMP sourced from 172.16.1.11 to vpn_server_1 or web servers times out.\n  - HTTP to http://172.16.1.21 and http://172.16.1.22 from host_1: repeated ~5s timeouts (no TTFB), indicating failure to establish TCP to the VPN endpoints.\n- Observation: systemctl reports wg-quick@wg0 “inactive (dead)” on host_1 and vpn_server_1, yet wg0 interfaces are present and “wg show” returns data. This suggests the interfaces may have been brought up outside of systemd. It does not, by itself, explain host_1’s lack of connectivity.\n\n3) Anomalies detected\n- Primary anomaly: The vpn_server_1 does not have a WireGuard peer configured for host_1.\n  - vpn_server_1 /etc/wireguard/wg0.conf shows the host_1 peer section commented out.\n  - vpn_server_1 wg show lists only peers for web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2; host_1’s public key is absent.\n- Resulting behavior:\n  - host_1 cannot complete WireGuard handshakes with vpn_server_1 and cannot exchange overlay traffic to 172.16.1.21/22.\n  - Application (HTTP) access from host_1 to the web servers fails because they only listen on VPN IPs.\n- Secondary note: HTTP is not listening on 20.0.0.x on the web servers (by design), so despite underlay ping reachability to 20.0.0.x, HTTP remains unreachable without a functioning VPN.\n\n4) Fault localization\n- Faulty device: vpn_server_1 (configuration).\n- Related endpoints: host_1 (client) is configured but cannot connect due to server-side missing peer config.\n- Non-faulty components: Internal routers, gateway_router, external_router_1, and web servers’ VPN sessions to the server (172.16.1.21/22) all appear healthy.\n\n5) Root cause\n- Misconfiguration on vpn_server_1: host_1’s WireGuard peer entry is missing/disabled (commented out). Without a corresponding peer/AllowedIPs on the server, host_1’s handshake is not accepted and return traffic for 172.16.1.11 cannot be routed over the tunnel. Consequently, host_1 cannot reach the VPN-only web services on 172.16.1.21/22.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 18037, "output_tokens": 4126, "total_tokens": 22163, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 17280}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2880}}}
